. @angus-c @gbrits I ran into a similar case. I think 'extending' existing components could be valuable in certain situations. I'm currently doing something similar to this (which is probably against Flight's philosophy and a terrible idea but I find it useful):

``` js
function extend(/*mixins*/) {
  var mixins = utils.toArray(arguments);
  var parentMixins = this.prototype.mixedIn;

  return define.apply(this, parentMixins.slice(3).concat(mixins));
}
```

the `extend` is attached to `Component` in `definde`

``` js
Component.extend = extend;
```

This allows for something like this:

base component

``` js
function (defineComponent, withMixin1, withMixin2) {
  return defineComponent(base, withMixin1, withMixin2);

  function base() {
    this.hello1 = function () {
      console.log('hello from base...');
    }
  }
}
```

another component

``` js

  function (BaseComponent) {
    return BaseComponent.extend(anotherComponent);

    function anotherComponent() {
      this.hello2 = function () {
        console.log('hello from another component...');
      }

      this.after('initialize', function () {
        this.hello1(); // hello from base...
        this.hello2(); // hello from another component...
      });
    }
  }
```
. haha I knew you will like the `slice` :). :+1:  for the hook. 
. @dannymidnight have you thought about using a promise in this case? For example:

``` js

$.ajax('/hello', { context: this }).then(function () { 
  this.trigger('world'); 
});
```
. +1
It seems like the CommonJS style is more readable (my personal opinion) when there are more dependencies involved. Another bonus is that one doesn't have to worry about the order of dependencies between `define` and the callback. 
