BugiDev:
Hello guys, 
is there any progress on this topic?
What do you think about this idea: 
Add the possibility to create the array of mixins that should be, in addition to existing ones, added to the base component. This array can be stored in, for example, requireJSs config (but this might be risky because the requireJS doesn't have a public API to access the config file but there is a hack for that) or to store it in the separate .json file. 
. @kmargaritis I had the same prroblem and I have managed to make it work, but you must change the flight's files to enable this.
First, create a require module for private jquery (jquery that is not in global scope):

```
jquery-private.js
-------------------------
define(['jquery'], function ($) {
    'use strict';
    return $.noConflict( true );
});
```

then, in your require config file, add the paths to `jquery` and `jquery-private` and map the request to `jquery` to route to `jquery-private`.

```
common.js
------------------
requirejs.config({
    baseUrl: 'your/base/path',
    paths: {
        'flight': '../libs/flight',
        'jquery': 'jquery/jquery',
        'jquery-private': '../libs/jquery-private'
    },
    map: {
        // '*' means all modules will get 'jquery-private'
        // for their 'jquery' dependency.
        '*': { 'jquery': 'jquery-private' },

        // 'jquery-private' wants the real jQuery module
        // though. If this line was not here, there would
        // be an unresolvable cyclic dependency.
        'jquery-private': { 'jquery': 'jquery' }
    }
});
```

after you have done that, you will have to include the dependency for `jquery` everywhere you want to use it:

```
define(
    [
        'flight/lib/component',
        'jquery'
    ],
    function (defineComponent, $) {
        'use strict';
        //here you can use $.('something')
}
```

Now comes the tricky part. You will have to change these Flight files to make it work: `base.js ; component.js ; logger.js ;  utils.js`

The only change that you have to make is to add the `jquery` dependency and to use it as a $ sign:

```
utils.js
-----------------------------

define(

  ['./debug','jquery'],

  function(debug, $) {
    'use strict';
    // Flight code for utils.js ...
}
```
. @kmargaritis It would definitely suite my project. :)
IMO, even if you keep the changes to flight's files as i wrote in previous post, you will not have any errors, because it is only the difference in whether you are using private jquery or not. I haven't tested this but, because you can load the jquery in require, and because the special treatment of jquery in require, it will add the jquery by default to global scope, and that is the wanted behavior as it is used now in Flight.
But, if you want to use private jquery, you can only make the change in require config file as I showed, and it will work because of the changes in Flight.

So, my proposal is to add the changes to the Flight and document the usage of jQuery as a separate page, so that devs will know that they can use either jQuery as a `<script>` , to add it to require on the global scope, or to add it as private jQuery, not polluting the global scope.
